observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Create an Inventory Committee whose members are capable, within the allocated time frame for physical inventory, to conduct a complete physical count of PPE in accordance with COA Circular 2020-006 and ensure timely submission of RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
Require the GSO-Designate and the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain an updated Property Cards and PPELC, respectively, per category on all PPE as recorded in the books of accounts, and regularly coordinate with each other so as to reconcile the discrepancies in the respective PPE accounts;
For missing PPE items which can no longer be found/located despite great effort, we recommended that Management strictly follow the guidelines of Section 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the disposition of non-existing/missing PPE items of government agencies; and
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to depreciate all PPEs annually in accordance with the regulations in order to reflect the accurate and reliable value of PPE in the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Strictly comply with the above-mentioned laws, rules and regulations relative to granting and liquidation of CAs;
Require the erring Officials and employees still connected with the LGU to immediately settle or refund their outstanding CAs, otherwise, impose appropriate legal actions to enforce its collections or settlement;
Regarding those no longer connected with the LGU, the Management may send demand letters to their home or known address, if possible;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to strengthen its internal control in CAs such as (i) do not authorize or facilitate additional CAs to Officers and employees if the previous CA balance is unsettled; (ii) enforce the immediate liquidation/settlement of long outstanding CAs; (iii) do not approve the clearance from money and property accountability of retiring, resigning or transferring Officers and employees, if their respective CAs’ are not settled; and
File a request for write off of those dormant CAs or ten years past due as well as CA of deceased AOs, in accordance with the guidelines provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to strengthen its internal control in the pre-audit of financial transactions and ensure that the supporting documents were complete and accurate;
Require the Municipal Engineer to submit to the Office of the Auditor the detailed engineering documents of the aforementioned projects to facilitate the technical review and evaluation;
Direct Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly comply with the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 regarding procurement planning, eligibility requirements and posting requirements to establish the regularity of the procurement process and the award of contract; and

We recommended that Management:
Ensure that the PO must be properly and completely accomplished with all the necessary information or data as required in the prescribed form before processing the financial transaction;
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to institute adequate internal control in the pre-audit of financial transactions and devise means to ensure that any deficiencies noted in the PO will be immediately rectified by Management and expedite the processing of transaction; and
Adhere strictly to the proper and complete documentary requirements relative to the procurement of goods stated under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

a.	Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the monthly reports, disbursement vouchers and its supporting documents to COA within ten calendar days of the ensuing month as prescribed in the rules;
b.	Hire additional competent staff or personnel in the Accounting Office, if the LGU has available budget, to cope with the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality so as to expedite the submission of accounts to the Auditor; and
c.	Evaluate the process of preparing the DVs, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents and devise measures to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must be undertaken when they were properly approved and with complete documentation.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the LGU officials and employees to submit promptly their claims together with complete relevant supporting documents to the Office of the Municipal Accountant;
Hire additional competent staffs and personnel in the Accounting Office to accommodate the voluminous transactions occurring each month in the Municipality, and to hasten the process of submission of the necessary accounts to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate the process of preparing the disbursement vouchers, RCIs, RCDs, RAAFs, and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years and be reminded that processing of vouchers must only be undertaken when they are properly approved and with complete documentation; and
Remind the concerned officials and employees of the administrative or criminal liability, under Section 39 (1) (3) of Presidential Decree (PD) No. 1445 and Article 218 of the Revised Penal Code, as amended by Section 41 of RA No. 10951, which may be imposed as a consequence of their inability or refusal to render accounts without justifiable cause.

We recommended that Management:
Direct officers and employees with cash advances to immediately submit their liquidation papers, otherwise, require the immediate withholding of salary of those officers and employees who were unable to comply with the requirement;
Require the Municipal Accountant to closely monitor the liquidation of outstanding cash advances and send written demand on the submission of liquidation report within the reglementary period;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and take legal actions against former employees, who are no longer in the government service, with unliquidated cash advances; and
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the cash advances of the deceased and separated accountable officers and conduct verification, analysis and validation of these cash advances to determine their settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:
Verify with the Supplier of the printers as to the status of the procurement, fast-track its implementation or cancel the contract and re-bid the same project;
Require the LSB to formulate a three-year program for strategic allocation of the SEF for public schools’ needs, and fast-track the approval of the LGU’s CDP and LDIP for better consideration of the same in the formulation and preparation of the SEF Budget;
Give preferential attention to the allocation and implementation of PPAs that could help support public schools in their operations and maintenance through the Annual SEF Budget; and
Strictly observe the provisions of DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 in the utilization of the SEF for its intended purpose.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Accountant to strengthen its internal control in the pre audit of financial transactions. Ensure that the supporting documents were complete and properly accomplished/filled out as to details and necessary information; otherwise, refrain from processing the claim or payment of the same. 

Revisit COA Circular No. 2012-001 for reference of supporting documents for common government transactions; 

Require the Property Officer to compel the Vendor/ Seller of the Land to produce the CT or TCT of the Land, and the LGU must register the same immediately in the Register of Deeds; 

In case the vendor still fails to deliver the Certificate of Title of the Land despite due demand, the LGU must rescind the Contract of Sale of Land and require the vendor to return the payment made for the Land, accordingly;

Require also the Vendor to comply/ submit the other lacking documents specified in COA Circular 2012-001, if still not submitted to the LGU; and

Submit the aforesaid lacking documents prescribed in COA Circular No. 2012-001 and rectify the deficiencies of the above-mentioned financial transactions in order to avoid suspension/ and or disallowance in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Make representations with the DBP for reconciliation of their records and obtain copies of debit memos and other related loan documents as reference in adjusting the books to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;

Strengthen accounting controls over loans payable by reviewing thoroughly the amortization schedule given by the bank and carefully analyzing transaction before recording in the books and updating entries of both records; 

Reclassify the non-current portion of the Loans Payable – Domestic account amounting to ₱48.73 million to its proper classification in the Statement of Financial Position; and

Disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the details of the Loans Payable – Domestic pursuant to Paragraph 127 of IPSAS No. 1.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Hire additional competent staffs and personnel in the Accounting Office to hasten the process of submission of the trial balances and financial statements to the Office of the Auditor;

Evaluate the process of preparing the reports and relevant documents to prevent further occurrence of this deficiency in the succeeding years;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly observe the timeline for the submission of financial reports especially the monthly Trial Balances that used to be neglected by the LGU; and

Come up with accounting procedures/methods to cope up with the submission of accounting reports to COA as well as other financial reports required by other agencies. Constantly remind/coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer and other concerned Offices within the LGU to submit the pending reports/ documents in order to avoid delay in the preparation and submission of financial reports to COA.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Accountant to strengthen its internal control in the pre audit of financial transactions. Ensure that the supporting documents were complete and properly accomplished/filled out as to details and necessary information; otherwise, refrain from processing the claim or payment of the same; 

Remind the Municipal Treasurer to refrain from making Cash Advances for catering services and the payment must be made directly to Supplier;

Submit the lacking documents and rectify the deficiencies of the above-mentioned financial transactions in order to avoid suspension/ and or disallowance in audit; and 

Require the Accountant to revisit the Revised Charts of Accounts for LGUs, with regard to proper classification/ identification of accounts relative to financial transactions of the LGU, especially in this instance, wherein the proper account used in catering services for LSI must be Welfare Goods Expense and not the Other Supplies and Materials Expense.

We recommended that Management require the LSB to:

Adhere strictly to the provisions of DepEd, DBM & DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017, particularly on the guidelines/timelines on the preparation of SEF Budget;

Formulate a three-year program for strategic allocation of the SEF for public schools’ needs. Give preferential attention to the allocation and implementation of PPAs that could help support public schools in their operations and maintenance through an Annual SEF Budget;

Be mindful and vigilant in the preparation of Municipality’s SEF Budget, taking into consideration the timelines of approval and submission to Provincial LSB so that the unfunded SEF programs/ proposals of the Municipality will be funded in the consolidated SEF Budget of the Province; and

Utilize the SEF Budget efficiently and effectively in accordance with the planned programs and activities that would help improve the operations of public schools for the benefit of the teachers, students and other stakeholders.

